'''Emmanuel Bushayija''' (born on 20 December 1960) is the titular [[King of Rwanda]]. He was proclaimed the titular King (''[[Mwami]]'') on 9 January 2017 to reign as '''Yuhi VI'''.<ref name="guardian20170112">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/12/rwandas-new-king-named-a-father-of-two-living-on-an-estate-near-manchester|title=Rwanda's new king named – a father of two living on an estate near Manchester|author=Frances Perraudin|date=12 January 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> He succeeded his late uncle King [[Kigeli V of Rwanda]] and is a grandson of [[Yuhi V of Rwanda|Yuhi V]].<ref>[http://king-kigeli.org/royal-news-and-events/item/65-announcement-of-new-head-of-the-royal-house Announcement of New Head of the Royal House], 9 January 2017.</ref>

== Biography ==
He grew up in exile in [[Uganda]], where he studied at Iganga Secondary School and worked for [[Pepsi|Pepsi Cola]] in [[Kampala]].

He also lived in Kenya, working in the tourism industry, before returning to Rwanda in July of 1994 – and then moving to the UK six years later.
The accession of Yuhi VI was made by proclamation of "the Royal Council of Abiru", who are a group of elders selected by the king and privy to his wishes. According to custom, the king selects his successor from among his family members. Bushayija, his nephew, was named as his successor. The announcement was made by Boniface Benzinge, chairman of the Abiru council.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/12/rwandas-new-king-former-pepsi-salesman-residing-cheshire/|title=Rwanda's new king is former Pepsi salesman residing in Cheshire|author=Adrian Blomfield|date=12 January 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref>

He lives in [[Manchester]].<ref name="guardian20170112" />

==Title and style of address==
* His Majesty the [[List of kings of Rwanda|Mwami of Rwanda]] (titular, 2017–present).

