== Eastern Europe ==

===Armenia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Armenia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Armenia}}

Prostitution in [[Armenia]] is illegal<ref name="stats">{{cite web|url=https://news.am/eng/news/125553.html|title=Prostitution statistics in Armenia|publisher=|accessdate=24 December 2016}}</ref> under [[administrative law]]<ref name="ency">{{cite book|last1=Ditmore|first1=Melissa Hope |title=Encyclopedia of prostitution and sex work|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=978-0313329685|page=90}}</ref> (Article 179.1).<ref>{{cite web|title=Republic of Armenia Law Enforcement Anti-Trafficking Training Needs Assessment|url=http://www.osce.org/yerevan/30894?download=true|website=[[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]|accessdate=19 January 2018|date=December 2007}}</ref> Related activities such as running a brothel and pimping are prohibited by the Criminal Code,<ref name="chartsbin" /><ref name="criminal">{{cite web|title=Criminal Code of the Republic of Armenia|url=https://prostitution.procon.org/sourcefiles/ArmeniaCriminalCode.pdf|publisher=National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia|accessdate=19 January 2018|date=18 April 2003}}</ref> although there are known to be brothels in the capital, [[Yerevan]], and in [[Gyumri]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dudwick|first1=Nora |last2=Gomart|first2=Elizabeth|last3=Marc|first3=Alexandre|last4=Kuehnast|first4=Kathleen|title=When things fall apart : qualitative studies of poverty in the former Soviet Union|date=2003|publisher=World Bank|location=Washington, DC|isbn=9780821350676|page=138}}</ref> According to [[UNESCO]], since the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] in 1991, prostitution in the country has grown.<ref name="hovhannisyan">{{cite web|title=Proposed to legalize prostitution in Armenia|url=https://report.az/en/region/proposed-to-legalize-prostitution-in-armenia/|website=Report News Agency|accessdate=19 January 2018|language=en|date=14 June 2015}}</ref> There are about 5,600 women involved in prostitution in Armenia,<ref name="unaids" /> roughly 1,500 of them are in Yerevan.<ref name="state9">{{cite web|title=Armenia 2009 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/eur/136018.htm|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=19 January 2018|date=11 March 2010}}</ref> However, official police figures are far lower, for example 240 in 2012.<ref name="stats" /> Police and other safety forces reportedly tolerate prostitution.<ref name="state9" /> Many women turn to prostitution due to unemployment.<ref name="iwpr">{{cite web|url=https://iwpr.net/global-voices/armenia-women-driven-prostitution|title=Armenia: Women Driven into Prostitution|publisher=|accessdate=24 December 2016}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Azerbaijan===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Azerbaijan}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Azerbaijan}}
Prostitution in [[Azerbaijan]] is illegal<ref name="admin">{{cite web|title=The Code of the Azerbaijan Republic On administrative violations|url=http://www.parliament.am/library/varchakaniravaxaxtumner/Azrbaijan.pdf|publisher=National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref> but common.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex-tourism in Azerbaijan: an Arabian summer|url=https://jam-news.net/?p=58286|website=JAM News|accessdate=15 February 2018|date=12 September 2017}}</ref> Prostitution is an administrative offence and punishable by a fine.<ref name="admin" /> Keeping a brothel is a criminal offence and punishable by up to 6 years imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Criminal Code of the Azerbaijan Republic|url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/az/az017en.pdf|publisher=National Assembly of the Azerbaijan Republic|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref> In 2017 a draft law proposing to add heavy fines to the punishment for keeping a brothel was before the [[National Assembly (Azerbaijan)|National Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Azerbaijan to impose heavy fines for prostitution and gambling|url=http://en.apa.az/azerbaijan-politics/domestic-news/azerbaijan-to-impose-heavy-fines-for-prostitution-and-gambling.html|website=APA Information Agency|accessdate=15 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> It has been estimated that there are 25,054 prostitutes in Azerbaijan,<ref name="unaids" /> some of which are aged 15  – 18.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prostitution gets younger in Azerbaijan|url=https://news.am/eng/news/73832.html|website=News AM|accessdate=15 February 2018|language=en|date=12 September 2011}}</ref> 
{{clear}}

===Belarus===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Belarus}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Belarus}}
Prostitution is illegal<ref name="chartsbin" /><ref name="ency" /> in [[Belarus]] but commonplace<ref>{{cite web|last1=Preiherman|first1=Yauheni|title=Minsk Police Cracks Down On Prostitution in Elite Clubs|url=https://belarusdigest.com/story/minsk-police-cracks-down-on-prostitution-in-elite-clubs/|website=BelarusDigest|accessdate=1 February 2018|date=13 June 2012}}</ref> and is an administrative, rather than criminal, offence.<ref name="chartsbin" /><ref name="ency" /> Running a brothel is forbidden and engaging in other means of pimping are punishable by up to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=On Amending Certain Codes of the Republic of Belarus to Increase Liability for Human Trafficking and Other Related Offences|url=http://www.osce.org/odihr/20922?download=true|publisher=Republic of Belarus|accessdate=1 February 2018|date=April 2003}}</ref> UNAIDS estimated there were 22,000 sex workers in Belarus in 2016.<ref name="unaids">{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Bulgaria===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Bulgaria}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Bulgaria}}
Prostitution itself is legal, but organised prostitution (brothels, prostitution rings, or other forms of procuring) is prohibited.<ref name="state.gov">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100552.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights in Bulgaria |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> Because of poor socioeconomic conditions, a high number of [[Romani people|Romani]] women are involved in prostitution.<ref name="state.gov"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Libby Gomersall|title= Reading Room: Bulgaria's working girls|work=[[The Sofia Echo]]|date=13 Aug 2007|url= http://sofiaecho.com/2007/08/13/655260_reading-room-bulgarias-working-girls|accessdate=2011-10-07}}</ref>

Bulgaria originally gained a reputation as a transit country for human trafficking, but subsequently, it has become known as a destination where the sex trade takes place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78805.htm|title=Country Report on Human Rights in Bulgaria|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://sofiaecho.com/2003/09/04/633579_fighting-the-sex-trade|title=Fighting the Sex Trade|author=Elena Kodinova|date=4 September 2003|website=sofiaecho.com|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>

The Bulgarian government has stepped up its efforts to eradicate human trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The sex trade is a major source of income for Bulgarian criminals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3071975/|title=Country report: Bulgaria|author=David Binder|date=|website=NBC News|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4532617.stm | work=BBC News | title=Sex trade's reliance on forced labour | date=2005-05-12 | accessdate=2010-05-22 | first=Jorn | last=Madslien}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/email/idUSL1291056220071212 | agency=Reuters | title=Crime gangs make billions from Bulgaria sex slaves | date=2007-12-12}}</ref> In 2013 there were 20,000 Bulgarian prostitutes working abroad and this was a source of foreign exchange earnings for Bulgaria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/159277/Thank+God+For+Bulgarians+Abroad|title=Thank God For Bulgarians Abroad|author=Georgi Papakochev|date=26 March 2014|website=novinite.com|accessdate=2 November 2015|via=Deutsche Welle}}</ref>
In the past, the Bulgarian government considered fully legalizing and regulating prostitution.<ref>{{cite news|author=Nicholas Kulish|url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/learn/news/bulgaria-moves-away-legalizing-prostitution|title=Bulgaria moves away from legalising prostitution|newspaper=International Herald Tribune|publisher=Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter|date=October 5, 2007|accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Czech Republic===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Czech Republic}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br />Buying sex legal<br />Brothels illegal<br />Procuring illegal<br />Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in the Czech Republic}}

In the [[Czech Republic]], prostitution is legal, but brothels and other forms of procuring are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dutchamsterdam.nl/232-prostitutes-age-limits-amsterdam |title=Red Light District – Age Limits for prostitutes and their clients. |website=DutchAmsterdam.com |date=4 August 2007 |access-date=2 November 2015}}</ref> The enforcement of these laws is lax, and prostitution and other activities which surround it are very common in the country.

Ever since the [[Velvet Revolution]] in [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1989 led to the creation of the two independent states [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]], prostitution has been flourishing, and has contributed its share to the region's booming tourist economy. It is widespread in [[Prague]] and areas near the Republic's borders with Germany and Austria. In 2002, the Czech Statistical Bureau estimated the trade to be worth six billion [[Czech koruna]] ($217 million) a year.<ref name="Mark McDaid">{{cite web|url=http://www.iamexpat.nl/read-and-discuss/expat-page/news/legal-age-for-prostitution-raised-Amsterdam|title=Legal age for prostitution raised in Amsterdam|author=Mark McDaid|date=8 March 2013|website=IamExpat|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Georgia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Georgia (country)}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Georgia (country){{!}}Prostitution in Georgia}}
In [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], prostitution is illegal<ref name="chartsbin" /> but widespread, particularly in the capital, [[Tbilisi]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morrison|first1=Thea|title=PM Addresses Alleged Prostitution and Discrimination at Tbilisi Nightclubs|url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/5574/PM-Addresses-Alleged-Prostitution-and-Discrimination-at-Tbilisi-Nightclubs-|website=Georgia Today on the Web|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=11 January 2017}}</ref> Many [[NGO]]'s attribute this to the harsh economic conditions according to the [[US State Department]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100560.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Georgia |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> Prostitution occurs on the streets,<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgia|url=http://swannet.org/en/countries/georgia|website=SWAN|accessdate=18 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> in bars, nightclubs,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mielnikiewicz|first1=Justyna|last2=Rimple|first2=Paul|title=Georgia: Teenage Prostitution Part of a Bigger Problem|url=https://eurasianet.org/s/georgia-teenage-prostitution-part-of-a-bigger-problem|website=Eurasianet|accessdate=18 February 2018|language=en|date=1 August 2014}}</ref> hotels and brothels.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kharshiladze|first1=Giorgi|last2=Ghudushauri|first2=Giorgi|title=No comment - What happens outside Tbilisi's brothels|url=https://www.georgianjournal.ge/society/29339-no-comment-what-happens-outside-tbilisis-brothels.html|website=GeorgianJournal|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=15 January 2015}}</ref> UNAIDS estimate there are 6,525 prostitutes in Georgia.<ref name="unaids" />

The [[Black Sea]] resorts, especially Gonio, become a sex tourism destination in the summer months. many prostitutes, mainly [[Central Asia]]n and from the [[North Caucasus]] come to the area. Due to the close proximity of the Turkey border, and no vista requirements for Turks, many men from Turkey come to the area to find prostitutes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Imedaishvili|first1=Nata|title=Locals Helpless As Sex Tourism Hits Georgian Black Sea Village|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/locals-helpless-as-prostitutes-take-over-georgian-village/24638723.html|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|accessdate=18 February 2018|language=en|date=8 July 2012}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Hungary ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Hungary}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Hungary}}

Prostitution is legal and regulated in Hungary. (It has been legalized and regulated by the government since 1999.) Under the law, prostitutes are professionals who engage in sexual activities in exchange for money. The government allows this activity as long as they pay taxes and keep legal documents.

In 2007, the prostitution and [[pornography]] industry in Hungary was estimated by Hungary's tax authority APEH to generate $1 billion annually.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gorondi|first1=Pablo|title=Hungary Gives Permits to Prostitutes|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/24/AR2007092400842.html|website=Washington Post|accessdate=17 December 2017|date=24 September 2007}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Kazakhstan===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Kazakhstan}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Kazakhstan}}
In [[Kazakhstan]] prostitution itself is legal, but acts facilitating prostitution, such as operating a [[brothel]] or prostitution ring, are illegal. Forced prostitution and prostitution connected to organized crime are prohibited. NGOs reported that criminal prostitution rings often included local law enforcement officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100615.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Kazakhstan |publisher=US Department of State |date=11 March 2008 |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref>

Estimates of the number of prostitutes in Kazakhstan vary from 4,000<ref name="eurasianetkaz" /> and 25.000,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://swannet.org/node/556 |title= Prostitution in Kazakhstan: abuse and risk |last= Aliya |first= |date= 28 August 2007 |website= SWAN |publisher= |access-date= 20 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref> including a number from [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Uzbekistan]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref name="eurasianetkaz">{{cite web |url= http://www.eurasianet.org/node/80201 |title= Kazakhstan: Sex Workers Call for Legalization of Prostitution |last= Emrich-Bakenova |first= Saule |date= 18 August 2016 |website= EurasiaNet |publisher= |access-date= 19 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref>

Sex workers often face harassment, extortion, arbitrary arrest, rape and violence from the police.<ref name="spl" />
{{clear}}

===Moldova===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Moldova}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Moldova}}
Prostitution in [[Moldova]] is an illegal activity but is widespread<ref name="welcome">{{cite web |url= https://www.welcome-moldova.com/articles/prostitution.shtml |title= Prostitution: Prosperous Purgatory |last= Mamaliga |first= Ludmila |date= |website= Welcome Moldova |publisher= |access-date= 2 December 2017 |quote= }}</ref> and socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/dec/02/anthonybrowne.theobserver |title= Drugs push scarred land to the brink |last= Browne |first= Anthony |date= 2 December 2001 |website= The Guardian |publisher= |access-date= 1 December 2017 |quote= }}</ref>

Morals Police captain Vladimir Istrati is quoted as saying "Prostitution in Moldova is a very well organised crime, there is a precise structure of operation which includes secretary, office and owner." The secretary is hard to file evidence against because they are most likely to conceal their true activity behind offering exotic services over the phone. Nailing down prostitutes and pimps is easier."<ref name="welcome" />
{{clear}}

=== Poland ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Poland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Poland}}

In [[Poland]] prostitution is legal, but operating brothels or other forms of pimping or coercive prostitution and prostitution of minors are prohibited, as is living off someone else's prostitution.<ref>[http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WDU19970880553 Kodeks karny Art. 204].</ref>

Prostitution is present in various forms in the country and a 2007 US State Department report stated that many women who worked as prostitutes were employed in massage parlors and escort services that functioned as brothels, although technically illegal.<ref name=izdebski>[http://gateway.nlm.nih.gov/MeetingAbstracts/ma?f=102232814.html Izdebski Z, Boron-Kaczmarska A; International Conference on AIDS. New prostitution phenomena in Poland. Int Conf AIDS. 1998; 12: 1159-60 (abstract no. 60869)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211215515/http://gateway.nlm.nih.gov/MeetingAbstracts/ma?f=102232814.html |date=February 11, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100578.htm |title=2007 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices in Poland |publisher=US State Department |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>
Prostitution is the only profession in Poland that is not taxed, but sex workers may be asked by authorities to prove that is what they do, since prostitution is not recognized as legitimate work, and therefore receive no social benefits.
<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbj.pl/article-53241-poles-claim-prostitution-for-tax-purposes.html?typ=ise|title=Poles claim 'prostitution'- for tax purposes. Warsaw Business Journal Feb 14 2011|publisher=}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Romania===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Romania}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Romania}}
Prostitution in [[Romania]] is not itself criminalized, although associated activities, such as [[Procuring (prostitution)|procuring]], are criminal offenses, and [[solicitation]] is a contravention punishable by fines.

Solicitation is an administrative offence (''contravenție'') punishable by a fine of 500–1500 [[Romanian leu|lei]] (approximately 110–330 [[euro]]s as of 2016).<ref>{{cite web|title=Romania|url=http://swannet.org/en/countries/romania|website=SWAN|accessdate=24 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> The National Police, Local Police and Gendarmes are all responsible for enforcing the laws, although there are reports that law enforcement is corrupt and that police are often violent.<ref name="spl">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=24 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> 

Clients are not prosecuted, unless they knowingly use the services of a victim of [[forced prostitution]],<ref>https://legeaz.net/noul-cod-penal/art-216</ref> or the prostitute is a minor (Art. 216''1'').<ref>https://legeaz.net/noul-cod-penal/art-216</ref>

Article 213<ref>https://legeaz.net/noul-cod-penal/art-213</ref> criminalizes procuring; it states that "The causing or facilitation of the practice of prostitution or the obtaining of financial benefits from the practice of prostitution by one or more individuals shall be punishable by no less than 2 and no more than 7 years of imprisonment and a ban on the exercise of certain rights." In certain aggravated circumstances, the punishment increases. The penal code also criminalizes several offenses against [[slavery]], [[human trafficking]], [[child trafficking]], [[forced labour]], and using [[Exploitation of labour|exploited persons]] (Art. 182 ''Exploitation of a person'', Art. 209 ''Slavery'', Art. 210 ''Trafficking in human beings'', Art. 211 ''Trafficking in underage persons'', Art. 212 ''Pressing into forced or compulsory labor'', Art. 216 ''Use of an exploited person’s services'').<ref name="legeaz.net">{{cite web|url=http://legeaz.net/noul-cod-penal/|title=Noul Cod Penal actualizat 2017 - Legea 286/2009|website=legeaz.net|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>

===Russia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Russia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Russia}}

Prostitution is an administrative, but not criminal, offence in Russia (such as, for example, drinking beer in a public place or walking nude on the street). The maximum punishment is a [[Fine (penalty)|fine]] up to 2000 [[Russian ruble|rubles]] (~$65); however, organising prostitution or engaging somebody into prostitution is punishable by a prison term.
{{clear}}

=== Slovakia ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Slovakia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
Prostitution itself is legal, but operating brothels and other activities related to prostitution are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100584.htm |title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices in the Slovak Republic |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> Public order offences are used against women who work on the streets.<ref name="spl" />
{{clear}}

===Ukraine===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Ukraine}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Ukraine}}

Prostitution is illegal in [[Ukraine]], but is nevertheless widespread and largely ignored by the government.<ref name="usds" /> Laws criminalizing organised prostitution and penalties for human trafficking have had little effect because many convicted traffickers often do not end up serving prison time.  The economic decline in Ukraine made the nation vulnerable and forced many to depend on prostitution and trafficking as a source of income.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theadvocatesforhumanrights.org/uploads/traffickingreport_2.pdf |title=Appendix I |website=''Theadvocatesforhumanrights.org'' |format=PDF |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> Sex tourism rose as the country attracted greater numbers of foreign tourists.<ref name="usds">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78846.htm|title=US Department of State: Ukraine|website=State.gov|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/apr/24/kiev-beautiful-women-sex-industry-ukrainian|title=Welcome to Kiev: city of beautiful women and a prospering sex industry|last=Antonova|first=Natalia|date=24 April 2012|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref>
{{clear}}

== Northern Europe ==

===Denmark===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Denmark}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Denmark}}

In [[Denmark]], prostitution was partly decriminalized in 1999, based partly on the premise that it was easier to police a legal trade than an illegal one. Third-party activities, such as profiting from brothel administration and other forms of procuring, remain illegal activities in Denmark, as do pimping and prostitution of minors.<ref name=statedep07>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100556.htm |title=Country Reports on Human Rights 2007: Denmark |publisher=US State Department |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecnnfreedomproject.blogs.cnn.com/2011/03/30/sex-trafficking-countries-take-different-approaches-to-same-problem/|title=The battle against sex trafficking: Sweden vs. Denmark |publisher=CNN|date=2011-03-30 |accessdate=2012-05-30}}</ref>

====Faroe Islands====
Under [[Courts of Denmark|Danish Jurisdiction]], the legal status of prostitution remains lawful. However, there is no evidence of organised prostitution within the self-governing territory.
{{clear}}

===Estonia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Estonia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Estonia}}
Prostitution in [[Estonia]] is legal in itself, but organized prostitution is illegal.  Since prostitution is a sensitive indicator that develops with changes in the social environment and the state, it is useful to divide the history of this phenomenon from Estonia's first independence according to the different historical stages of the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prostitution in Estonia |work=EQUAL |date= |url=http://www.tai.ee/failid/Prostitution_in_Estonia._ingl.pdf |accessdate= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930213904/http://www.tai.ee/failid/Prostitution_in_Estonia._ingl.pdf |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref>

Firstly, the period of [[Estonian War of Independence|Estonian independence]] 1918-1940, when the prostitution in Estonia was legalized. Secondly, the period of the [[Occupation of the Baltic states|Soviet occupation]] when prostitution was criminalized. Thirdly, since [[Singing Revolution|Estonian new independence]] when prostitution is neither criminalized nor legalized (that is, the selling of and buying of a sexual service is not a crime but prostitution is not considered a profession either).
{{clear}}

===Finland===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Finland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Finland}}

Prostitution itself is legal in Finland (soliciting in a public place is illegal), but organised prostitution, operating a brothel or a prostitution ring, and other forms of [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimping]]) is illegal. In June 2006, [[Eduskunta|parliament]] voted by 158 to 15 with four abstentions to approve a bill which outlaws the buying of sexual services from prostitutes if it is linked to human trafficking. According to a recent [[TAMPEP]] study, 69% of prostitutes are foreigners. As of 2009, there was little "visible" prostitution in Finland, as it was mostly limited to private residences and nightclubs in larger metropolitan areas.
{{clear}}

===Iceland===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Iceland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Iceland}}

Paying for sex is illegal in [[Iceland]] (the client commits a crime, but the prostitute does not).<ref name="jafnretti.is">{{cite web|url=http://www.jafnretti.is/jafnretti/?D10cID=ReadNews&ID=523 |title=Jafnréttisstofa |publisher=Jafnretti.is |date=2009-04-21 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>  The police have stated that they do not have the resources to enforce the law. Consequently, a vigilante group called "Stóra systir" ("Big Sister") has been formed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.icelandreview.com/icelandreview/daily_news/Big_Sister_Watches_Buyers_of_Prostitution_in_Iceland_0_383393.news.aspx |title=Big Sister Watches Buyers of Prostitution in Iceland |publisher=Iceland Review |date=19 October 2011}}</ref>

A report published in 2017 by the ''National Commissioner of the Icelandic Police'' states that prostitution had "exploded" in the previous 18 months.<ref name="icemon">{{cite web|title=Organized Crime and Prostitution on the rise in Iceland|url=https://icelandmonitor.mbl.is/news/politics_and_society/2017/10/26/organized_crime_and_prostitution_on_the_rise_in_ice/|website=Iceland Monitor|accessdate=2 February 2018|date=26 October 2017}}</ref> The vast majority of prostitutes in the country are foreign.<ref name="icemon" /> Police believe prostitution in Iceland is partially tied to [[organised crime]] and human trafficking.<ref name="icemon" />

The country has become a sex tourism destination.<ref name="icerev">{{cite web|last1=Hafstað|first1=Vala|title=Sex Tourism a Problem in Iceland|url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2015/08/26/sex-tourism-problem-iceland|website=Iceland Review|accessdate=2 February 2018|language=en|date=26 August 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Ireland===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Ireland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in the Republic of Ireland}}

Prostitution itself is legal in the Republic of Ireland, however since March 2017, it has been an offence to buy sex.<ref name="enact">{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Elaine|title=Minister for Justice signs new laws on sexual offences|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/minister-for-justice-signs-new-laws-on-sexual-offences-1.3026288|website=The Irish Times|accessdate=14 April 2018|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref> Third party involvement. such as operating brothels, and other forms of pimping) are also illegal.<ref name="clsoa93">{{cite web|title=Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Act, 1993|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/20/enacted/en/html|website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB)|language=en}}</ref> Although the 2017 law criminalising clients was designed to reduce the demand for prostitution,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farrell|first1=Alan|title=Opinion: Buying a woman's body for sexual gratification is not a harmless act|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/readme/sex-workers-in-ireland-1896233-Jan2015/|website=TheJournal.ie|accessdate=14 April 2018|language=en|date=25 January 2015}}</ref> the law has had little effect.<ref>{{cite web|last1=MacNamee|first1=Garreth|title=Buying sex has been illegal in Ireland for one year but 'very little' has changed|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/sex-workers-ireland-laws-3865840-Feb2018/|website=TheJournal.ie|accessdate=14 April 2018|language=en|date=23 February 2018}}</ref>

Most prostitution in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] occurs indoors and is advertised via the internet. Street prostitution has declined considerably.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher|first1=Conor|title='It's clearly a brothel, yet nothing can be done'|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/it-s-clearly-a-brothel-yet-nothing-can-be-done-1.3168979|website=The Irish Times|accessdate=14 April 2018|date=29 July 2017}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Latvia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Latvia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Latvia}}

Prostitution is legal and regulated in [[Latvia]]. Prostitutes must register, must undergo monthly health checks, and must carry a health card; if they fail to do so, they can be penalized.<ref name="vvc.gov.lv">{{cite act|url=http://www.vvc.gov.lv/export/sites/default/docs/LRTA/MK_Noteikumi/Cab._Reg._No._32_-_Restriction_of_Prostitution.doc|title=Regulations Regarding Restriction of Prostitution|format=doc|type=Regulation|number=32||date=22 January 2008|access-date=10 October 2017}}</ref> Although prostitution is regulated in Latvia, brothels and other forms of procuring are illegal. According to the law, "Any activity of the third person which promotes prostitution is prohibited", and, "Persons are prohibited to join in groups in order to offer and provide sexual services".<ref name="vvc.gov.lv"/>
{{clear}}

===Lithuania===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Lithuania}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Lithuania}}
Prostitution in [[Lithuania]] is illegal, but it is common.<ref name="chartsbin">{{cite web |url= http://chartsbin.com/view/snb |title= The Legal Status of Prostitution by Country |last= |first= |date= |website= Charts Bin |publisher= |access-date= 27 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref><ref name="procon">{{cite web|title=100 Countries and Their Prostitution Policies|url=https://prostitution.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=000772#greece|website=Procon|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> Law enforcement is weak,<ref name="spl" /> corrupt<ref name="ipf" /> and is reputedly connected to [[organised crime]].<ref name="spl" /> It is estimated that there are 3,000 prostitutes in the capital [[Vilnius]].<ref name="ipf">{{cite web|title=Lithuania|url=http://www.policy.hu/kalikov/LITHUANIA.html|website=International Policy Fellowship|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> Many of them are foreign, predominantly [[Russia]]n, but there are also significant numbers from [[Belarus]], [[Ukraine]] and [[Poland]].<ref name="ipf" /> [[Street prostitution]], including underage prostitutes,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chaplinskas|first1=S.|last2=Mårdh|first2=P. A.|title=Characteristics of Vilnius street prostitutes|pmid=11231871|journal=International Journal of STD & AIDS|volume=12|issue=3|pages=176–180|doi=10.1258/0956462011916983|date=2001}}</ref> is generally controlled by criminal elements.<ref name="ipf" />
{{clear}}

===Norway===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Norway}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Norway}}

Paying for sex is illegal (the client commits a crime, but the prostitute does not). This law prohibiting the buying of sexual services (sexkjøpsloven) came into effect on January 1, 2009, following the passing of new legislation by the [[Storting]] in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7806760.stm |title=New Norway law bans buying of sex. BBC News Jan 1 2009 |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2013-10-18}}</ref> Soliciting and advertising "sexual services" is also illegal under the Norwegian Criminal Code (''Straffeloven'') section 378 and section 202(3).<ref>[http://nppr.se/2011/10/07/the-sale-of-sexual-services-in-norway-legal-but-still-illegal/ The sale of sexual services in Norway: legal, but still illegal? Sunniva Schultze-Florey. Nordic Prostitution Policy Reform. 7 July 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131226161851/http://nppr.se/2011/10/07/the-sale-of-sexual-services-in-norway-legal-but-still-illegal/ |date=26 December 2013 }}</ref>

In 2013, it was estimated there were 3,000 sex workers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/sexarbeider-tapte-parole-kampen-1.11520429|title=Sexarbeider tapte parole-kampen|first=|last=NRK|publisher=}}</ref> working in Norway<ref name=taxing/> ([[Demographics of Norway|population]] 5 million).<ref>[http://www.ssb.no/a/english/kortnavn/folkendrkv_en/2012k4/hittil00-en.html Population per 1 January 2013 and population changes in 2012. Counties] SSB, retrieved 14 September 2013</ref> Earnings from sex trade are estimated at 390 million [[Norwegian krone|kroner]] (£39m, $US63m, €48m).<ref name=taxing>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/a-taxing-issue-for-norways-sex-workers-8861316.html|title=A taxing issue for Norway's sex workers|date=6 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Sweden===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Sweden}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Sweden}}

Paying for sex is illegal (the client commits a crime, but not the prostitute). The Sex Purchase Act (''Sexköpslagen''), which makes it illegal to pay for sex, but not to be a prostitute, was adopted in 1999, and was then unique. Since then, similar laws have been passed in [[Norway]] and [[Iceland]].

The rationale underpinning the law was the view that prostitution was a form of [[violence against women]] so the crime consists in the customer paying for sex, not in the prostitute selling sexual services.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jean-Michel |url=http://sisyphe.org/spip.php?article1424 |title=Sweden Treating Prostitution as Violence Against Women |publisher=Sisyphe.org |date= |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> This 'rationale' sees the seller of sex as the exploited partner in the exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sweden.gov.se/sb/d/3926/a/47455 |title=Chapter 6 of the Swedish Penal Code 1962:700 |publisher=Sweden.gov.se |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===United Kingdom===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|United Kingdom}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal except in Northern Ireland<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in the United Kingdom}}

In [[Great Britain]], prostitution itself is legal,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7736436.stm | work=BBC News | title=Q&A: UK Prostitution Laws | date=2008-11-19 | accessdate=2010-05-22 | first=Dominic | last=Casciani}}</ref> but a number of related activities, including soliciting in a public place, [[Kerb crawler|kerb crawling]], keeping a brothel, [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimping]], and [[Procuring (prostitution)|pandering]], are outlawed.

The [[Policing and Crime Act 2009]] makes it illegal to pay for sex with a prostitute who has been "subjected to force", and this is a ''strict liability offence'' (clients can be prosecuted even if they didn't know the prostitute was forced).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2009/ukpga_20090026_en_4#pt2-pb1-l1g14 |title=Policing and Crime Act 2009 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nodo50.org/Laura_Agustin/unworkable-ways-to-stop-trafficking-uk-law-on-exploitation-and-gain |title=Policing and Crime &#124; UK &#124; Anti-trafficking &#124; Exploitation &#124; Sex Industry &#124; The Naked Anthropologist |publisher=Nodo50.org |date=2010-04-06 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>

In [[Northern Ireland]], which previously had similar laws to the rest of the United Kingdom, paying for sex became a crime when the Human Trafficking and Exploitation (Criminal Justice and Support for Victims) Act (Northern Ireland) 2015 was enacted in January 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-30805990|title = Human Trafficking Bill receives Royal Assent|last = |first = |date = 14 January 2015|work = BBC News|access-date = 27 January 2015}}</ref>

====Guernsey====
{{main|Prostitution in the Crown dependencies#Bailiwick of Guernsey}}
Prostitution in Guernsey is legal, but related activities such as [[solicitation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Summary Offences (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Law, 1982|url=http://www.guernseylegalresources.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=71011&p=0|website=Guernsey Legal Resources|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref> and [[brothel]] keeping are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ordonnance relative aux Maisons de Prostitution et aux Prostituées - [1906]|url=http://www.guernseylegalresources.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=98780&p=0|website=Guernsey Legal Resources|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref> At the end of the 19th century [[prostitution]] was common in [[Guernsey]], especially in [[St Peter Port]] where around 500 soldiers were garrisoned. A large number of the prostitutes were [[France|French]].

====Isle of Man====
{{main|Prostitution in the Crown dependencies#Isle of Man}}
Prostitution is legal in the Isle of Man but related activities such as soliciting, [[procuring (prostitution)|procuring]] and brothel keeping are prohibited by the Sexual Offences Act 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sexual Offences Act 1992|url=http://www.legislation.gov.im/cms/images/LEGISLATION/PRINCIPAL/1992/1992-0006/SexualOffencesAct1992_1.pdf|website=Isle of Man Legislation|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>

There are few prostitutes permanently on the [[Isle of Man]], most visiting the island on short term "tours".<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man Escorts, IOM Escorts|url=https://www.selectanescort.com/escorts/IsleofManEscorts.html|website=Select An Escort Directory|accessdate=19 February 2018|language=en-UK}}</ref> A man and a woman were arrested on suspicion of committing prostitution offences in [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] in 2013. A police spokesman said this was "an unusual and rare incident."<ref>{{cite web|title=Pair arrested over prostitution offences {{!}}  Isle of Man News :: isleofman.com|url=http://www.isleofman.com/news/details/57787/pair-arrested-over-prostitution-offences|website=IsleOfMan.com|accessdate=19 February 2018|language=en|date=3 September 2013}}</ref>

====Jersey====
{{main|Prostitution in the Crown dependencies#Bailiwick of Jersey}}
Prostitution in Jersey is legal,<ref name="itv">{{cite web|title=Jersey hotels warned of the signs of prostitution|url=http://www.itv.com/news/channel/2015-02-05/jersey-hotels-warned-to-look-out-for-prostitution/|website=ITV News|accessdate=19 February 2018|language=en|date=5  February 2015}}</ref> but related activities such as keeping a brothel are outlawed.<ref name="beeb">{{cite web|title=Prostitution laws 'could be updated'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-jersey-32789334|website=BBC News|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref name="jep">{{cite web|title=Fall in number of prostitutes advertising in Jersey|url=https://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2015/02/06/fall-in-number-of-prostitutes-advertising-in-jersey/|website=Jersey Evening Post|accessdate=19 February 2018|language=en|date=6 February 2015}}</ref> Following a consultation period from 1 September 2017 and the 13 October 2017, the Home Affairs Minister approved a new draft Sexual Offences (Jersey) Law to be debated in the [[States of Jersey|Assembly of the States of Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sexual Offences Draft Law|url=https://www.gov.je/News/2018/Pages/Sexualoffenceslaw.aspx|website=Information and public services for the Island of Jersey|accessdate=19 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> The draft law does not criminalise prostitution, but consolidates previous legislation on related activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Consultation draft - Sexual Offences (Jersey) Act|url=https://www.gov.je/SiteCollectionDocuments/Government%20and%20administration/Consultation%20Draft%20-%20Sexual%20Offences%20(Jersey)%20Law%20201-%20(002)%20V2.pdf|website=Information and public services for the Island of Jersey|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>

In 2015 it was estimated there were 35–40 prostitutes in [[Jersey]].<ref name="itv" /> Most visit the island for short periods and work from hotels.<ref name="jep" />

== Southern Europe ==

===Albania===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Albania}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Albania}}
Prostitution in [[Albania]] is illegal but widespread.<ref name="chartsbin" />

Prior to the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|collapse of the Soviet Union]] in the early 1990s, prostitution in Albania was virtually unknown. The migration from rural areas to the cities, and economic problems that followed the collapse caused some women to turn to prostitution.<ref name="swan">{{cite web|title=Sex Work in Albania – an Overview|url=http://swannet.org/node/1041|website=SWAN|accessdate=14 February 2018|language=en|date=1 October 2006}}</ref>

Street prostitution occurs near the centre of the capital, [[Tirana]], mainly by [[Romani people|Roma]] men and women.<ref name="swan" /> Some students work as prostitutes from hotels or motels in Tirana and other big cities. Brothels also found in the cities.<ref name="swan" />
{{clear}}

=== Andorra===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Andorra}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Andorra]] is illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100545.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Andorra |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Bosnia and Herzegovina===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
Prostitution in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] is legal, but related activities such as solicitation and keeping a brothel are illegal.<ref name="spl" /> The law treats procuring as a major crime. Under the law, trafficking is a state-level crime that carries a sentence of up to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100551.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Bosnia and Herzegovina |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> In 2016, [[UNAIDS]] estimated there to be 4,000 prostitutes in the country.<ref name="unaids" />
{{clear}}

=== Croatia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Croatia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Croatia}}
Prostitution in [[Croatia]] is illegal,<ref name="spl" /> but common.<ref name="procon" /> Forcible prostitution, any kind of brothels, or procuring are treated as felony, while voluntary prostitution is considered to be infraction against public order (for prostitutes only; clients are not in violation of law). Like in many other Southeast European countries, the problem of human trafficking for the purposes of sex is big in Croatia. However, according to the U.S. State Department, Croatia is a tier 1 country, actively working to prevent the sex trade.<ref name=croatia_illegal>{{cite web| url = https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78806.htm| title = Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Croatia| date = 2007-03-06| accessdate = 2008-10-10| website = [[United States Department of State]]}}</ref><ref name=bulgaria_trafficking>{{cite web| url = http://www.sofiaecho.com/article/mixed-results-against-people-trafficking-in-south-eastern-europe/id_29987/catid_68| title = Mixed results against people trafficking in South-Eastern Europe| date = 2008-06-17| last = Leviev-Sawyer| first = Clive
| accessdate = 2008-10-10| website = SofiaEcho.com}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Cyprus===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Cyprus}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Cyprus}}
The law does not prohibit prostitution itself, but operating [[brothels]], organizing prostitution rings, living off the profits of prostitution, encouraging prostitution or forcing a person to engage in prostitution are illegal activities.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100554.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Cyprus |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>

Cyprus has been criticised by the US State Department <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MXH6mQ9yWUU |title=Cyprus's Struggle with the Sex Trade |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref> for failing to control the flow of illegal immigrants and legal to be involved in forced prostitution. Cyprus has gained a reputation for being a major transit point for people smugglers to transport women for the purposes of prostitution. International observers have criticized the government for its lack of action to prevent forced prostitution. The law of Cyprus forbids forced (but not voluntary) prostitution. However, it is believed that many immigrants are hired as bar maids and coerced into prostitution by this method.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
{{clear}}

====Northern Cyprus====
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Northern Cyprus}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
The [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]] is only recognised as a separate state by [[Turkey]]. Prostitution is illegal, however in nightclubs, "konsomatrices", who sit with, eat with or entertain customers for money are allowed. Konsomatrices are not allowed to have sex with customers, but this restriction is frequently flouted.<ref>{{Cite journal|title= Sex Work and State Regulations in North Cyprus |last= Rodrígueza |first= Leopoldo |last2= Güven-Lisaniler |first2= Fatma |last3= Uðural
 |first3= Sevin |date= |publisher= The Pennsylvania State University |quote= |citeseerx = 10.1.1.691.6938}}</ref> Enforcement is generally lax, but in July 2006 the Nicosia District Court ordered the first prostitution-related imprisonment. After pleading no contest to the charges, the manager of Mexico nightclub, Mesut Kilicarslan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison for encouraging and profiting from prostitution. By the year's end three more suspects were sentenced to imprisonment for encouraging and profiting from prostitution.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

Northern Cyprus has become a destination for [[sex tourism]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cyprusupdates.com/2011/06/sex-tourism-is-booming-in-northern-cyprus/ |title= Sex tourism is booming in Northern Cyprus |last= |first= |date= 7 June 2011 |website= Cyprus Updates |publisher= |access-date= 25 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref>

===Gibraltar===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Gibraltar}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in the British Overseas Territories#Gibraltar}}
Prostitution is illegal in Gibraltar, as are related activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crimes Act 2011|url=http://www.gibraltarlaws.gov.gi/bills/bills2011/2011B07.pdf|website=HM Government of Gibraltar|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> Prior to its abolition in 1992 prostitution was concentrated in the red-light district of Seruya’s Ramp.<ref name="gib2">{{cite web|last1=Chipulina|first1=Neville|title=The People of Gibraltar - 1885 - James Joyce - Molly Bloom's Gibraltar - Part 3|url=http://gibraltar-intro.blogspot.co.uk/2016/08/1885-james-joyce-molly-blooms-gibraltar_83.html|website=Gibraltar Intro|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Greece===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Greece}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Greece}}
Prostitution is legal at the age of 18. Persons engaged in prostitution must register at the local prefecture and carry a medical card that is updated every two weeks. Greek authorities decided to implement a 1999 law which stipulates that all brothels must have permits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2002/18368.htm|title=Greece: Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|author=|date=31 March 2003|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> It is estimated that fewer than 1,000 women are legally employed as prostitutes and approximately 20,000 women, most of foreign origin, are engaged in illegal prostitution.<ref name="state1">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/eur/119082.htm |title=2008 Human Rights Report: Greece |publisher=State.gov |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9707/04/greece.albania.prostitutes/index.html | work=CNN | title=Albanians muscling in on Greek prostitutes | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> According to NGO estimates, there are 13,000-14,000 trafficking victims in the country at any given time. Major countries of origin for trafficking victims include Nigeria, Ukraine, Russia, Bulgaria, Moldova and Belarus.<ref name="state1"/>
{{clear}}

===Italy===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Italy}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Italy}}
[[File:10.3010 Torino-nightlife.v2.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A street prostitute talking to a potential customer in [[Torino]], Italy, 2005]]
In [[Italy]], prostitution, defined as the exchange of sexual acts for money, is legal, although organized prostitution, whether indoors in brothels or controlled by third parties, is prohibited. Brothels were banned in 1958. Single sex workers working from apartments are "tolerated". Loitering is permitted, but soliciting ("unabashedly inviting clients on the street") is illegal. Migrants with work or residence permits may work in sex work, and police cannot revoke residence permits and begin deportation procedures, as they tried failing by the Italian laws.

A 2008 report stated that were some 100,000 prostitutes in Italy.<ref name="itmag091008">{{cite web|url=http://www.italymag.co.uk/italy/crime/government-set-approve-anti-prostitution-bill |title=Government set to approve anti-prostitution bill |website=Italy Magazine |date=10 September 2008}}</ref>
In 2007 it was stated that the total number of workers was 70,000.<ref>{{cite web|author=in: Hot Issues |url=http://www.impactlab.com/2007/01/26/70000-prostitutes-in-italy |title=70,000 Prostitutes in Italy |publisher=Impact Lab |date=26 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stranitalia.com/home/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=148&Itemid=1 |title=Italy preparing to punish prostitutes and their clients |publisher=Stranitalia.com |date=13 September 2008}}</ref>
The Italian Statistics Institute stated the number of street workers in 1998 was 50,000.<ref name="dantuono">{{cite web|author1=A D'Antuono |author2=F Andalò |author3=E M Carlà |author4=S De Tommaso |url=http://sti.bmj.com/content/77/3/220.full |title=Prevalence of STDs and HIV infection among immigrant sex workers attending an STD centre in Bologna, Italy. D'Antuono A, Andalò F, Carlà EM, De Tommaso S. Sex Transm Infect. 2001 Jun;77(3):220 |website=BMJ |date=2 February 2001}}</ref>

A [[euphemism]] often used to refer to prostitutes in Italy is ''Lucciole'' (lit. "[[fireflies]]").
{{clear}}

=== Kosovo ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Kosovo}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Kosovo}}
Prostitution in [[Kosovo]] is illegal, and can incur a prison sentence of up to sixty days.<ref name="peace">{{cite web|title=Law on Public Peace and Order|url=https://www.kuvendikosoves.org/common/docs/ligjet/2009-142-eng.pdf|publisher=Assembly of Republic of Kosovo|accessdate=18 March 2018|date=17 September 2009}}</ref> [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]]'s HIV Program in Kosovo estimated there to be 5,037 prostitutes in the country.<ref name="selmani">{{cite web|last1=Selmani|first1=Arber|title=How Kosovo's Unregulated Sex Industry is a Danger to Public Health|url=http://balkanist.net/sex-workers-in-kosovo/|website=Balkanist|accessdate=18 March 2018|date=25 June 2016}}</ref> Many women turn to [[prostitution]] through poverty.<ref name="selmani" /> There are report that prostitution has become a new [[organised crime]] in Kosovo.<ref>{{cite web|title = Kosovo: Prostitution As A New Organized Crime Sideline|date = 21 June 2013|url = https://reportingproject.net/occrp/index.php/en/ccwatch/cc-watch-briefs/1998-kosovo-prostitution-as-a-new-organized-crime-sideline}}</ref>

Prior to the [[Kosovo War]] following the [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence]], prostitution was limited to serving the needs of locals.<ref name="beeb19">{{cite web|title=Kosovo UN troops 'fuel sex trade'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3686173.stm|website=BBC|accessdate=18 March 2018|date=6 May 2004}}</ref> Following the ceasefire and presence in the country of the [[United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo]] and other international organisations, the demand for prostitution soared. As well as women turning to prostitution voluntarily, some were trafficked from Moldova, Bulgaria and the Ukraine.<ref name="beeb19" />
{{clear}}

===Malta===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Malta}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Malta}}
Prostitution itself is legal,<ref name="times2">{{cite web|last1=Attard|first1=Eddie|title=Past laws regulating the oldest profession in Malta|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20140316/life-features/Past-laws-regulating-the-oldest-profession-in-Malta.511052|website=Times of Malta|accessdate=23 February 2018|date=16 March 2014}}</ref> but certain activities connected with it, such as running a brothel and loitering, are not. Certain offences are punishable by sentences of up to two years in prison.<ref name="state2">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/eur/119092.htm |title=2008 Human Rights Reports: Malta |publisher=State.gov |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>

In March 2008, police and the Ministry for Social Policy signed a memorandum of understanding to formalize a screening process for all arrested persons engaged in prostitution to determine whether they were victims of trafficking or other abuses.<ref name="state2"/> The law provides punishments of up to 6 years for involving minors in prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interpol.int/public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaMalta.asp|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20010927021208/http://www.interpol.int/public/children/sexualabuse/nationallaws/csamalta.asp|dead-url=yes|archive-date=27 September 2001|title=Sexual Offences Laws - Malta|author=|date=|website=interpol.int|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Montenegro===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Montenegro}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Montenegro]] is illegal.<ref name="chartsbin" />

Montenegro is a source, transit, and destination country for women and children subjected to sex trafficking. Victims of sex trafficking identified in Montenegro are primarily women and girls from Montenegro, neighbouring Balkan countries, and, to a lesser extent, other countries in Eastern Europe. Sex trafficking victims are exploited in hospitality facilities, bars, restaurants, night clubs, and cafes.<ref name="state17">{{cite web|title=Montenegro 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271246.htm|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Portugal===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Portugal}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Portugal}}

In Portugal, prostitution itself is legal, but it is illegal for a third party to profit from, promote, encourage or facilitate the prostitution of another.<ref>[http://www.archividelnovecento.it/archivinovecento/CAPPATO/Cappato/Faldone59-7Dirittiumani/prostituzione/seminarioPE/prostitution-PT.pdf Archivi Archivi del Novecento: Prostitution in Portugal - The legal framework] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722024156/http://www.archividelnovecento.it/archivinovecento/CAPPATO/Cappato/Faldone59-7Dirittiumani/prostituzione/seminarioPE/prostitution-PT.pdf |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref> Consequently, organized prostitution ([[brothel]]s, prostitution rings or other forms of [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimping]]) is prohibited.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100579.htm U.S. Departement of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor, ''2007 Country Report on Human Rights in Portugal'']: "Pimping and running brothels are illegal and legally punishable".</ref><ref name="IES">[http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/IES/portugal.html#8 Nuno Nodin et al. International Encyclopedia of Sexuality: Portugal. 8. Significant Unconventional Sexual Behaviors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316221829/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/IES/portugal.html |date=2013-03-16 }}</ref> Forced prostitution and human trafficking are also illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100579.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Portugal |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>

In the mid-2000s, the number of female prostitutes was estimated at 28,000, of which at least 50% were foreigners.<ref name="prostitution CM">{{pt icon}} João Saramago, [http://www.correiomanha.pt/noticiaImprimir.asp?idCanal=186&id=153608 Estrangeiras dominam prazer], [[Correio da Manhã]] (17 March 2005)</ref><ref name="ex.ac.uk prostitution in Portugal">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.ex.ac.uk/watupman/undergrad/aac/port.htm|title=Sex work and Sexual Exploitation in the European Union - The Situation in Portugal|author=|date=|website=ex.ac.uk|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Republic of Macedonia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Macedonia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in the Republic of Macedonia}}
Prostitution in the [[Republic of Macedonia]] is legal, though with various restrictions<ref name="spl" /> and common.<ref name="swannet-mac">{{cite web|title=Macedonia|url=http://swannet.org/en/countries/macedonia|website=SWAN|accessdate=22 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[UNAIDS]] estimate there are 3588 prostitutes in the country.<ref name="unaids" /> The Macedonian government is trying to clamp down on prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peacewomen.org/news/Macedonia/newsarchive03/sextrade.html|title=Sex Slave Racket Clampdown in Macedonia<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=peacewomen.org|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20040125004655/http://www.peacewomen.org/news/Macedonia/newsarchive03/sextrade.html |archive-date= 25 January 2004 }}</ref>

STAR-STAR (Association for support of marginalised workers) is a sex worker led support group. It's Executive Board is exclusively made up of sex workers. STAR-STAR was the first sex workers collective in the [[Balkans]].<ref name="swannet-mac" />

The country is a major transit point for prostitution to the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78826.htm|title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Macedonia|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gall |first=Carlotta |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F01E5DF133DF93BA15754C0A9679C8B63 |title=Macedonia Village Is Center Of Europe Web in Sex Trade - NYTimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date=2001-07-28 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref>  The trafficking of women for sex is worth billions in Macedonia and is considered to be run primarily by Albanian gangsters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3071971|title=Sex, drugs and guns in the Balkans|author1=David Binder|author2=Preston Mendenhall|date=2013|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===San Marino===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|San Marino}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[San Marino]] is illegal<ref name="chartsbin" /> and is not commonplace.<ref>{{cite web|title=San Marino  Country Reports on Human Rights Practices - 2006|url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/pages/attachments/2016/02/08/dos-hrr_2006_san-marino.pdf|publisher=US  Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|accessdate=24 February 2018|date=6 March 2007}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Serbia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Serbia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Serbia]] is illegal, and can incur a prison sentence of up to 30 days, and up to 60 days for minors. Pimping is illegal and can incur a prison sentence of between 6 months and 5 years, and between 1 and 10 years for pimping minors.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.blic.rs/vesti/politika/iskreno-ruzic-za-blic-legalizujte-prostituciju-politicari-redovno-idu-kod-prostitutki/zfdk9by|title=ISKRENO Ružić za "Blic": Legalizujte prostituciju, političari redovno idu kod prostitutki|language=sr|trans-title=HONESTY Ružić to "Blic": Legalize Prostitution, Politicians go to Prostitutes Rregularly|author1=Zorica Lazarević |author2=Miljana Leskovac|date=3 January 2015|newspaper=Blic}}</ref> UNAIDS estimate there to be 3,901 prostitutes in the country.<ref name="unaids" />

Following a large police action against prostitution in Belgrade's major hotels in late September 2017, [[Ministry of Public Administration and Local Self-Government (Serbia)|Minister of Public Administration and Local Self-Government]] [[Branko Ružić (politician)|Branko Ružić]] voiced support for legalizing and regulating prostitution.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.informer.rs/vesti/drustvo/153861/PROSTITUCIJU-SRBIJI-TREBA-LEGALIZOVATI-Ministar-Branko-Ruzic-okrio-kako-drzava-profitira-najstarijeg-zanata|title=PROSTITUCIJU U SRBIJI BI TREBALO LEGALIZOVATI! Ministar Branko Ružić otkrio kako da država PROFITIRA OD NAJSTARIJEG ZANATA!|language=sr|trans-title=PROSTITUTION IN SERBIA SHOULD BE LEGALIZED! Minister Branko Ružić reveals how the state would PROFIT FROM IT!|author=|date=26 September 2017|newspaper=Informer}}</ref> [[Serbian Radical Party]] president [[Vojislav Šešelj]] supported the proposal, under the condition that prostitutes undergo regular health checks for [[Sexually-transmitted Disease|sexually transmitted diseases]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.informer.rs/vesti/drustvo/153982/RADIKALNO-SESELJ-LEGALIZACIJU-PROSTITUCIJE-Lider-SRS-podrzava-inicijativu-ministra-Branka-Ruzica|title=RADIKALNO! I ŠEŠELJ JE ZA LEGALIZACIJU PROSTITUCIJE! Lider SRS podržava inicijativu ministra Branka Ružića!|language=sr|trans-title=RADICAL! ŠEŠELJ IS FOR THE LEGALIZATION OF PROSTITUTION! SRS leader supports the initiative of Minister Branko Ružić!|author=|date=27 September 2017|newspaper=Informer}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Slovenia ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Slovenia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
Prostitution in [[Slovenia]] was decriminalised in June 2003.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |editor1-last= Ramet |editor1-first= Sabrina P. |editor2-last= Fink-Hafner |editor2-first= Danica |date= 1 October 2006 |title= Democratic Transition in Slovenia: Value Transformation, Education, and Media |url= |location= |publisher= Texas A&M University Press |page= 223 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> Forcing others into prostitution is an offence under Article 175 of the Criminal Code.<ref>{{cite web|title=Criminal Code|url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/si/si045en.pdf|website=[[World Intellectual Property Organization]]|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Spain===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Spain}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal in certain areas
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Spain}}

Prostitution itself is legal in Spain, but [[pimping]] is not. Owning an establishment where prostitution takes place is legal if the owner neither derives financial gain from prostitution nor ''hires'' any person for the purposes of selling sex, because prostitution is not considered a job, and has no legal recognition. Most places do not regulate prostitution, but the government of Catalonia offers licenses for persons "to gather people to practice prostitution".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/6-23-2006-100298.asp |title=Europe's Brothel - in a Corner of Spain |publisher=Buzzle.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref> 
These licenses are used by brothel owners to open 'clubs', where prostitution takes place (the women are theoretically only 'gathered' to work on the premises not employed by the owner). Some places have implemented [[fine (penalty)|fines]] for street prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.typicallyspanish.com/news/publish/article_23597.shtml |title=Granada brings in hefty fines for street prostitution |publisher=Typicallyspanish.com |date=2009-10-22 |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/es/news/local_news/Seville-to-follow-Catalan-lead-with-bid-to-regulate-prostitution.html |title=Seville to follow Catalan lead with bid to regulate prostitution |publisher=Expatica.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Turkey===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Turkey}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Condoms mandatory<ref>{{cite web |last1=Özaşçılar |first1=Mine |last2=Ziyalar |first2=Neylan |title=Framing Prostitution in Turkey: News Media Coverage of Prostitution |url=http://www.sascv.org/ijcjs/pdfs/mineneylanijcjs2015vol10issue2.pdf |publisher=International Journal of Criminal Justice Sciences (IJCJS) |accessdate=16 July 2018 |date=2015}}</ref> 
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Turkey}}

In Turkey, prostitution is legal and regulated. Prostitutes must register and acquire an ID card stating the dates of their health checks. Also, it is mandatory for registered prostitutes to have regular health checks for sexually transmitted diseases. The police are allowed to check the authenticity of registered prostitutes to determine whether they have been examined properly and to ensure they see the health authorities if they don't. Men cannot register under this regulation. Most sex workers, however, are unregistered, as local governments have made it policy not to issue new registrations. As a result, most sex workers in Turkey are not registered sex workers, working in violation of the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2002/18396.htm|title=Turkey: Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|author=|date=31 March 2003|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/06/26/news/turkey.php |title=Turkey's sex trade entraps Slavic women |publisher=International Herald Tribune |date=27 June 2005 |author=Craig S. Smith |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604163042/http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/06/26/news/turkey.php |archivedate=4 June 2008 |df= }}</ref> Turkey is listed by the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|UNODC]] as a top destination for victims of human trafficking.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk"/>
{{clear}}

