== Western Europe ==

=== Austria ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Austria}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Austria}}
[[Image:Brothel-in-linz-20070628.jpg|thumb|left|Brothel in [[Linz]]]]
Prostituttion in [[Austria]] is [[regulated prostitution|legal and regulated]] under the [[penal code]] (''Strafgesetzbuch'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jusline.at/Strafgesetzbuch_%28StGB%29.html|title=Jusline: Strafgesetzbuch (StGB)|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>
under ''Zehnter Abschnitt Strafbare Handlungen gegen die sexuelle Integrität und Selbstbestimmung (§§ 201-220b)'' 
(Part Ten: Offences against sexual integrity and self-determination (§ § 201-220b)). Most sex workers are [[Immigration|migrants]], mainly from the former [[Eastern Bloc]]  countries.<ref name=sjoe>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjoe.at/content/frauen/themen/koerper/article/618.html|title=Sozialistische Jugend Österreich: Prostitution - zwischen Ablehnung, Marginalisierung und Akzeptanz. Interview with Eva van Rahden from SILA|publisher=[[Socialist Youth Austria]]|language=German|accessdate=18 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721232836/http://www.sjoe.at/content/frauen/themen/koerper/article/618.html|archive-date=21 July 2011}}</ref>
According to a 2010 [[TAMPEP]] study, 78% of sex workers in Austria are [[Alien (law)|foreigners]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://euobserver.com/9/29340|title=EU Observer: Romanian sex workers most prevalent in EU Jan 26 2010|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>

Although sex work itself is not forbidden, Section 207b<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jusline.at/207b_Sexueller_Missbrauch_von_Jugendlichen_StGB.html|title=Sexueller Missbrauch von Jugendlichen|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>''Sexueller Missbrauch von Jugendlichen'' (Sexual abuse of juveniles) allows for prosecution of clients of workers younger than 18.  Additional restrictions are specified in § 214 to 217. Medical examinations are required by the AIDS and STD laws.<ref name="Sila">{{cite web|url=http://en.sophie.or.at/basic_infos/prostitutions-gesetze/laws|title=Sophie: Laws on Prostitution|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> The laws of the federal [[States of Austria]] place further restrictions on the times and places where prostitution may occur.<ref name="LG_Prostitutio">[http://homepage.univie.ac.at/elisabeth.holzleithner/LG_Prostitution.htm Landesbestimmungen zur Ausübung der Prostitution] (June 28, 2007)</ref> The most restrictive law is that of [[Vorarlberg]], where prostitution is legal only in licensed brothels and to date no such licenses have been issued.<ref name="Sila"/>
{{clear}}

=== Belgium ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Belgium}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Belgium}}
[[Image:Aarschotstraat.jpg|thumb|left|[[Rue d'Aerschot]], [[Brussels]]: A portion of the street, with [[Red-light district|red lights]] and prostitutes visible.]]
Prostitution itself is legal in Belgium, but the law prohibits operating brothels and other forms of [[pimping]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100550.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Belgium |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> or assisting immigration for the purpose of prostitution. However, in practice enforcement can be lax and "unofficial" brothels are tolerated (for example in [[Antwerp]]). Human trafficking or exploiting individuals for financial gain is punishable for a maximum prison sentence of 30 years.<ref name="dos">{{cite web |url= https://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2010/142759.htm |title= Trafficking in Persons Report 2010 |last= |first= |date= 14 June 2010 |website= |publisher= [[U.S. Department of State]] |access-date= 11 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref>  A recent report by RiskMonitor foundation states that 80% of the prostitutes who work as windows prostitutes in Belgium are from [[Bulgaria]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Sex trafficking and money laundering: the case of Bulgaria|last = Petrunov|first = Georgi|publisher = Risk Monitor|year = 2009|isbn = |location = |url=http://www.riskmonitor.bg/js/tiny_mce/plugins/ajaxfilemanager/upload/Reports/RM-02-SexTrafficking_EN.pdf|pages = 16}}</ref> Belgium is listed by the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|UNODC]] as a top destination for victims of human trafficking.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/6497799.stm |title=Special Reports &#124; UN highlights human trafficking |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-03-26 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> Many sex workers organisations feel that the present grey area in which prostitution operates leaves sex workers vulnerable to exploitation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expatica.com/be/life_in.html |title=Life In Belgium |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3068827.stm |title=Making Sex Pay |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= 2003-07-17| work=BBC News | first=Clare | last=Murphy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/jun/24/andrewosborn.theobserver | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Squalid road that leads to Belgium | first=Andrew | last=Osborn | date=2001-06-24 | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2003-11-04-beligan-brothels_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=In Belgium, brothels are big business | first1=Noelle | last1=Knox | date=2003-11-04 | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Belgian Experiment: Make Prostitution Legal to Fight Its Ills    |work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=|url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB111706273289743489 |accessdate=2012-04-11}}</ref>

A report commissioned by the National Bank of Belgium,<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nbb.be/doc/dq/e/dq3/histo/ief0925.pdf|title = A new measure of the economic importance of prostitution in Belgium|last = National Bank of Belgium|first = |date = |work = |access-date = 3 December 2015|via = }}</ref> estimated a turnover of 840 million Euro in 2015.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = A direct measure of output in prostitution in Belgium|url = http://rgdoi.net/10.13140/RG.2.1.4868.6807|doi = 10.13140/rg.2.1.4868.6807|last1=Adriaenssens|first1=Stef|last2=Hendrickx|first2=Jef|last3=Machiels|first3=Thomas|last4=Heylen|first4=Wim|year=2015}}</ref> The most important segments of the market seem to be escort and private prostitution, rather than the more visible forms of window or street prostitution.
{{clear}}

=== France===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|France}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in France}}

Prostitution in [[France]] (the exchange of sexual acts for money) was legal until April 2016, but several surrounding activities were illegal, like operating a brothel, living off the avails (pimping), and paying for sex with someone under the age of 18 (the [[age of consent]] for sex is 15).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-25802279|title=Franck Ribery and Karim Benzema on trial over prostitute|website=BBC News}}</ref> On 6 April 2016, the French National Assembly voted to punish customers of prostitutes by a fine of €1500.<ref name="law16">[http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2016/04/06/prostitution-le-parlement-adopte-definitivement-la-penalisation-des-clients_4897216_3224.html Prostitution : le Parlement adopte définitivement la pénalisation des clients] 'Le Monde', accessed 7 April 2016</ref> The law has been evaluated as a failure, putting sex workers in danger, reducing prices, and decreasing condom use among their clients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2018/04/18/2782371-prostitution-moins-de-clients-plus-de-risques.html|title=Less clients, more risk|website=La Depeche}}</ref>

In the [[Napoleonic era]], France became the model for the regulatory approach to prostitution. In the 20th century, however, a policy shift became apparent. Brothels became illegal in 1946, and France signed the [[Convention for the Suppression of the Traffic in Persons and of the Exploitation of the Prostitution of Others]] in 1960. France thus became a major supporter of the international abolitionist movement for the eradication of prostitution.
{{clear}}

=== Germany ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Germany}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation restricted<br>Condoms mandatory<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzie |title=Germany makes having sex with prostitutes without condom illegal |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/germany-prostitution-law-condoms-sex-workers-bundesrat-vote-approved-date-comes-in-brothels-illegal-a7326056.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=10 June 2018 |date=23 September 2016}}</ref>
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Germany}}

Prostitution in [[Germany]] is  legal, as are all aspects of the sex industry, including brothels, advertisement, and job offers through HR companies. Full service sex work is widespread and [[Prostitution law|regulated]] by the [[Politics of Germany|German government]], which levies taxes on it.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Act Regulating the Legal Situation of Prostitutes – implementation, impact, current developments |publisher=Social Research Institute of Applied Sciences Freiburg |url=http://www.cahrv.uni-osnabrueck.de/reddot/BroschuereProstGenglisch.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref> In 2002, the government changed the law in an effort to improve the legal situation of sex workers. However, the social stigmatization of sex work persists and many workers continue to lead a [[double life]].<ref name=tampep>{{citation|url=http://tampep.eu/documents/wssw_2009_final.pdf|title=Final Report TAMPEP 8, Germany|work=[[TAMPEP]] reports|date=October 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720173715/http://tampep.eu/documents/wssw_2009_final.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Human rights organizations consider the resulting common exploitation of women from [[Eastern Europe|Eastern]] and [[Southeast Europe|Southeastern Europe]] to be the main problem associated with the profession.
{{clear}}

=== Liechtenstein ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Liechtenstein}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Liechtenstein]] is illegal, but is tolerated by the police as long as it is not [[street prostitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100568.htm|title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Liechtenstein|author=|date=11 March 2008|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaLiechtenstein.pdf |title=Legislation of Interpol member states on sexual offences against children - Liechtenstein |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-03-31  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714201203/http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaLiechtenstein.pdf |archive-date=14 July 2007}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Luxembourg===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Luxembourg}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation restricted
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Luxembourg}}
Prostitution itself is legal in [[Luxembourg]], but activities associated with organised prostitution, such as profiting from (operating brothels and prostitution rings) or aiding prostitution, are illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100570.htm |title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Luxembourg |publisher=State.gov |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> Human trafficking incurs severe penalties.<ref>
{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/hearings/20040119/femm/document1_en.pdf |title=A summary of the prostitution regulations in the EU member states |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=www.europarl.europa.eu |publisher=European Parliament |access-date=13 September 2015 |quote=Luxembourg: Procuring is prohibited, and the keeping of brothels. Buying sex from children under 18 is illegal, but prostitution in itself is not criminal.}}</ref>
<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78825.htm|title=Country Report on Human Rights Practices in Luxembourg|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> There are estimated to be 300 [[prostitute]]s in [[Luxembourg]], most of whom are immigrants.<ref name="exeter">{{cite web|title=How many Prostitutes?|url=http://people.exeter.ac.uk/watupman/undergrad/aac/scale.htm|website=Exeter University|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>

Street prostitution is only permitted in two streets near [[Luxembourg City]]'s [[Luxembourg railway station|railway station]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schalekamp|first1=Mark|title=This is Europe|date=2016|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9789081656603|url=https://books.google.com/?id=15RNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT96&lpg=PT96&dq=street+prostitution+in+luxembourg#v=onepage&q=street%20prostitution%20in%20luxembourg&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and only between 20:00 and 03:00. The area is regulated by the city authorities, and patrolled regularly by the police. Prostitutes working outside these streets or outside the permitted times may be arrested and fined up to €2,500. Because of the number of prostitutes and limited area to work in, some work from other streets near the legalised area and risk being arrested.<ref name="services">{{cite web|title=Sex Work|url=http://www.services4sexworkers.eu/s4swi/articles/view/id/21|website=Services4SexWorkers|accessdate=21 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> 
{{clear}}

===Monaco===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Monaco}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in Monaco}}

Prostitution itself is legal in Monaco, but organized prostitution (brothels, prostitution rings and other forms of [[pimping]]) is prohibited. Solicitation is also illegal. Forcing another person into prostitution is illegal, with penalties from six months to three years of imprisonment, plus a fine. A husband who forces his wife to engage in prostitution can be sentenced to one to five years of imprisonment plus a fine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2003/27855.htm|title=Monaco|website=U.S. Department of State}}</ref><ref name="mono">{{cite web|url=http://www.monacohebdo.mc/5792-prostitution%E2%80%89-pas-de-sanction-pour-les-clients|title=Prostitution?: Pas de sanction pour les clients|website=Monaco Hebdo}}</ref>

Prostitution takes place most commonly in hotels, bars and nightclubs.<ref name="mono"/> 
{{clear}}

===Netherlands===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Netherlands}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Solicitation legal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in the Netherlands}}
[[File:Prostata Prostitute.jpg|thumb|left|Scene from [[Amsterdam]]'s red light district.]]

Prostitution is legal and regulated in the Netherlands. Operating a brothel is also legal. In the last few years, a significant number of brothels and "windows" have been closed because of suspected [[criminal activity]]. [[De Wallen]], the largest and best-known red-light district in Amsterdam, is a destination for international sex tourism.

Prostitution  is concentrated in and around the big cities and in the border towns in the regions of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]], [[Groningen (province)|Groningen]], [[Twente]], [[North Brabant|West Brabant]] and [[Zeeland]]. Prostitution occurs in various forms: 'window' and street prostitution, clubs, escort agencies and home-based prostitution. 'Window' prostitution occurs in 12 cities in the Netherlands. It is estimated that on average some 2,000 prostitutes are engaged daily in this form of prostitution. Street prostitution exists in 10 Dutch cities and involves on average some 320 prostitutes daily. Between 3,500 and 4,000 prostitutes are employed daily in 600–700 clubs and private brothels. The extent of other forms of prostitution such as escort agencies and home-based prostitution is much more difficult to estimate. Home-based prostitution occurs in at least 17 municipalities and escort agencies exist in at least 28 municipalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/faq-prostitution-netherlands |title=FAQ – Prostitution in the Netherlands &#124; Radio Netherlands Worldwide |publisher=Rnw.nl |accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Switzerland ===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Switzerland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation legal in designated areas
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Switzerland}}

Full service sex work in [[Switzerland]] is legal and regulated; it has been legal since 1942. Trafficking, forcing people into prostitution and most forms of pimping are illegal.<ref name=Independent>{{cite newspaper|title= Drive-in sex plan to curb prostitutes in Europe's playground  |newspaper= The Independent|date=1 August 2011|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/drivein-sex-plan-to-curb-prostitutes-in-europes-playground-2330219.html|location=London|first=Charlotte|last=McDonald-Gibson}}</ref> Licensed [[brothel]]s, typically with a reception and leading to several [[studio apartment]]s, are available. One estimate puts the number of street sex workers in Zurich at 5000.<ref name=Independent/>

The majority of sex workers are foreigners from the Americas, [[Central Europe]] or the [[Far East]]. In recent years the number of full service sex workers has increased. Many workers operate using newspaper advertisements, [[mobile phone]]s and secondary rented apartments, some accept [[credit card]]s.
{{clear}}

