Nigerians are one of the most misunderstood people in Africa, [[Stereotypes of Africans|by both other Africans]] and non-Africans. There are some stereotypes typically associated with Nigerians and these are both positive and negative. Apart from the general stereotypes, there are peculiar stereotypes concerning the ethnic groups in Nigeria that even other Nigerians believe and propagate.

== Positive stereotypes ==

=== Open mindedness ===
It is generally believed that Nigerians are open-minded and quick to try new things.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalstereotype.com/nigerian-stereotypes/|title=Nigerian Stereotypes|work=National Stereotypes|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Hardworking ===
Nigerians are generally regarded as hard-working people who are willing to go the extra mile for success.<ref name=":0" />

=== Proud and happy ===
Nigerians are regarded as a very proud people. They also feature as one of the happiest people on earth.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://thetab.com/us/brown/2016/02/08/americans-dont-know-nigeria-1976|title=I'm sick of the stereotypes Americans have about Nigeria|date=2016-02-08|work=The Tab Brown|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Negative stereotypes ==

=== Nigerians are into advance fee fraud ===
This stereotype is mainly a product of the many Nigerian prince 419 scams which were popular. Many people believe that a large percent of Nigerians are into internet scam and fraud. While it is true that some youths take to it, the stereotype is essentially misplaced as the number of youths partaking in this is minimal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://buzznigeria.com/nigerians/#|title=10 Stereotypes of Nigerians that aren’t Always True|last=Partners|first=Alexander Moore|date=2014-07-17|work=Nigeria News Online & Breaking News {{!}} BuzzNigeria.com|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref> Most internet scammers simply prefer to use Nigeria and Nigerian identities in their schemes.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

=== Nigerians are poor ===
This stereotype stems from the general perception that Africans are poor and in need of charity. It is important to note that Nigerians have some of the richest people in the world. [[Aliko Dangote]], a Nigerian, is the richest black man alive. The percentage of poor Nigerians is not as high as this stereotype portrays it.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

=== Nigerians are uneducated ===
This is one of the negative stereotypes about Nigerians. It is generally believed by most non-Nigerians that Nigerians are not well educated and cannot speak English.<ref name=":1" /> This is a myth as Nigerians have one of the highest literacy rates in Africa and English is the official language in Nigeria due to its multi-ethnic status.

